<subSubSection id="13E4654DFF9D1576EC44FA4FFA5BFA39" box="[538,1446,1484,1523]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" type="nomenclature">
4.— 
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576EC3DFA4FFBDFFA39" box="[611,1058,1484,1523]" class="Reptilia" family="Deinodontidae" group="Deinodont Group" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="group">The Deinodont Group</taxonomicName>
of the Cretaceous
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="13E4654DFF9D1576EF11F98BFAAFF9AB" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" type="description">
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576EF11F98BFDFDF9E5" box="[335,512,1544,1583]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576EF11F98BFE07F9E5" authorityName="Leidy" authorityYear="1856" box="[335,506,1544,1583]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Deinodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Deinodon</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
including 
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576ECB5F98BFC3CF9E5" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1866" box="[747,961,1544,1583]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Gorgosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576ECB5F98BFC3CF9E5" box="[747,961,1544,1583]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Gorgosaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576EA18F98BF98EF9E5" box="[1094,1651,1544,1583]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576EA18F98BFAC0F9E5" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[1094,1341,1544,1583]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Albertosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Albertosaurus</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576EB2AF98BF995F9E5" authority="Marsh, 1877" authorityName="Marsh" authorityYear="1877" box="[1396,1640,1544,1583]" class="Reptilia" family="Dryptosauridae" genus="Dryptosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Dryptosaurus</taxonomicName>
;
</emphasis>
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576EC2FF9B9FC79F9AB" box="[625,900,1594,1633]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576EC2FF9B9FC83F9AB" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[625,894,1594,1633]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Tyrannosaurus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
including 
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576EA17F9B9FAAFF9AB" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[1097,1362,1594,1633]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Dynamosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576EA17F9B9FAAFF9AB" box="[1097,1362,1594,1633]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Dynamosaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</subSubSection>
</paragraph>
<subSubSection id="13E4654DFF9D1579EFFFF9FDFDCBFBAA" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="375" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" type="description">
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF9D1576EFFFF9FDFCD7F8A4" blockId="7.[334,1653,1484,2490]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
This group includes the large Upper Cretaceous dinosaurs. 
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576E85FF9FDFE38F91D" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1866" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Gorgosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576E85FF9FDF988F96F" box="[1537,1653,1662,1701]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576EF11F933FE38F91D" box="[335,453,1712,1751]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Gorgosaurus</emphasis>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576EC71F933FCDCF91D" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[559,801,1712,1751]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Albertosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576EC71F933FCDCF91D" box="[559,801,1712,1751]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Albertosaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are very probably identical with 
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576EBE0F933F98DF91D" box="[1470,1648,1712,1751]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576EBE0F933F997F91D" authorityName="Leidy" authorityYear="1856" box="[1470,1642,1712,1751]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Deinodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Deinodon</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576EFFFF961FD56F8C3" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[417,683,1762,1801]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Dynamosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576EFFFF961FD56F8C3" box="[417,683,1762,1801]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Dynamosaurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576ED45F961FAB0F8C3" box="[795,1357,1762,1801]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576ED45F961FBD7F8C3" authorityName="Osborn" authorityYear="1905" box="[795,1066,1762,1801]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Tyrannosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Tyrannosaurus</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576EA02F961FAB0F8C3" authority="Marsh, 1877" authorityName="Marsh" authorityYear="1877" box="[1116,1357,1762,1801]" class="Reptilia" family="Dryptosauridae" genus="Dryptosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Dryptosaurus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
is provisionally held distinct from 
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576ECEEF897FC9CF8F1" box="[688,865,1812,1851]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF9D1576ECEEF897FCA6F8F1" authorityName="Leidy" authorityYear="1856" box="[688,859,1812,1851]" class="Reptilia" family="Tyrannosauridae" genus="Deinodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Deinodon</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
which it much resembles. The essential features of this group are:
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF9D1576EF3CF8FDFC11F86A" blockId="7.[334,1653,1484,2490]" box="[354,1004,1918,1952]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">1.—Gigantic size and massive proportions.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF9D1576EF3CF82BFA67F7BA" blockId="7.[334,1653,1484,2490]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">2.—Skull relatively large with long deep jaw and large teeth. All fenestrse more or less reduced and arcades massive. Anterior teeth of U-shaped cross-section, (both crests posterior) the form changing progressively to the compressed oval section of the posterior teeth, with anterior and posterior serrate crest. Premaxillary teeth in the above genera much reduced in size.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF9D1576EF3CF7F4FD73F709" blockId="7.[334,1653,1484,2490]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">3.—Quadrate closely united to quadratojugal, elongate, extending backward and downward.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF9D1576EF3CF749FC8AF726" blockId="7.[334,1653,1484,2490]" box="[354,887,2250,2284]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">4.—No fronto-parietal movement.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF9D1576EF3CF777FCD3F6DC" blockId="7.[334,1653,1484,2490]" box="[354,814,2292,2326]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">5.—Cervicals short and wide.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF9D1576EF3DF69FF9C8F6F4" blockId="7.[334,1653,1484,2490]" box="[355,1589,2332,2366]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
6.— 
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF9D1576EFFDF69FFE14F6F4" box="[419,489,2332,2366]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Fore</emphasis>
limb greatly reduced in relative size, moderately slender throughout.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF9D1576EF3AF6C6FD54F670" blockId="7.[334,1653,1484,2490]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">7.—Manus peculiarly specialized, me. I very short and stout, me. II much longer, me. Ill vestigial, distal ends of metacarpals deeply grooved, phalanges rather short.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF921579EEFBFE1EFB0FFE75" blockId="8.[145,1463,413,2476]" box="[165,1266,413,447]" pageId="8" pageNumber="375">8.—Ungual phalanges of manus strongly curved and much compressed.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF921579EEFBFE44FC86FDF7" blockId="8.[145,1463,413,2476]" pageId="8" pageNumber="375">9.—Pelvic bones usually solidly united. Ilium elongate, extended far forward and decurved anteriorly with very short peduncle, ischium flattened distally and decurved, not expanded at the tip.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF921579EECAFDC6FE6EFD5B" blockId="8.[145,1463,413,2476]" pageId="8" pageNumber="375">10.—Tibia and femur of subequal length, pes stout and massive and of moderate length.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF921579EECAFD1BFACFFC7D" blockId="8.[145,1463,413,2476]" pageId="8" pageNumber="375">11.—Lateral metatarsals massive, moderately long, median metatarsal broader than either at distal end, but the shaft greatly reduced, in the distal portion trigonal, the inferior sides closely appressed to the lateral metatarsal shafts, in the proximal portion reduced to a very slender rod between the lateral shafts; the head a little enlarged but enclosed dorsad and plantad by the large heads of the lateral metatarsals. The distal ends of the lateral mestarsals are convex both ways, that of the median plano-convex</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF921579EECAFC3CFDF4FBC6" blockId="8.[145,1463,413,2476]" pageId="8" pageNumber="375">12.—Phalanges of pes massive and rather short, the unguals moderately curved, uncompressed.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF921579EECAFB90FDCBFBAA" blockId="8.[145,1463,413,2476]" pageId="8" pageNumber="375">13.—Tail elongate, the distal caudals strongly interlocked by prolongation of the prezygapophyses.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="13E4654DFF921579EEB8FBF0FE48F666" pageId="8" pageNumber="375" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF921579EEB8FBF0FABFF77C" blockId="8.[145,1463,413,2476]" pageId="8" pageNumber="375">
The above analysis of characters shows that the deinodonts, although paralleling the megalosaurs in their huge size, massive proportions, short neck and large head, differ from them and resemble the coelurids and ornithomimids in the construction of the pelvis and the elongate quadrate. The pes has the very peculiar and specialized character of the Ornithomimidse very exactly reproduced, save for the greater massiveness of all its elements; the manus is nearer to that of the Cceluridae in some respects than to the megalosaurs, despite the diversity in the length of the phalanges, but might almost equally well be regarded as a specialization from that of 
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF921579EC81F9B4FC5AF994" box="[735,935,1591,1630]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="375">
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF921579EC81F9B4FC5FF994" authorityName="Marsh" authorityYear="1877" box="[735,930,1591,1630]" class="Reptilia" family="Allosauridae" genus="Allosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="8" pageNumber="375" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Allosaurus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
A review of the characters indicates that this group is not derived from the megalosaurs but from some primitive coelurosaurian with the specialized pes of the 
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF921579EAB5F91FFF05F93F" authorityName="Marsh" authorityYear="1890" class="Reptilia" family="Ornithomimidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="8" pageNumber="375" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Ornithomimidae</taxonomicName>
, but with the fore limb constructed more as in 
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF921579EAFFF94DFAACF93F" authorityName="Marsh" authorityYear="1881" box="[1185,1361,1742,1781]" class="Reptilia" family="Coeluridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="8" pageNumber="375" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Coeluridae</taxonomicName>
or in 
<emphasis id="698AEAD4FF921579EECDF883FEA0F8ED" box="[147,349,1792,1831]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="375">
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF921579EECDF883FEABF8ED" authorityName="Marsh" authorityYear="1877" box="[147,342,1792,1831]" class="Reptilia" family="Allosauridae" genus="Allosaurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="8" pageNumber="375" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Allosaurus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
although smaller and with the phalanges less elongate than in 
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF921579EE95F8B1FE9DF893" authority="Marsh, 1879" authorityName="Marsh" authorityYear="1879" box="[203,352,1842,1881]" class="Reptilia" family="Coeluridae" genus="Coelurus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="8" pageNumber="375" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Coelurus</taxonomicName>
. Such a type would probably be a slender, small, swiftfooted animal, for only in such a type can one understand the evolution of the remarkable specialization of the pes. The subject of the affinities and origin of the various groups of theropod dinosaurs will be ably and thoroughly discussed in an essay by Doctor von Huene to be published elsewhere, and the foregoing data, based upon comparison of the theropod skeletons on exhibition in the American Museum, are intended only to present the reasons for the taxonomic arrangement here adopted.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5B4136C6FF921579EEBBF743FE48F666" blockId="8.[145,1463,413,2476]" pageId="8" pageNumber="375">
The point which we principally desire to make clear is that upon the above evidence the 
<taxonomicName id="9CFE4D45FF921579EFADF772FD0CF6D2" authorityName="Cope" authorityYear="1866" box="[499,753,2289,2328]" class="Reptilia" family="Deinodontidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dinosauria" pageId="8" pageNumber="375" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Deinodontidae</taxonomicName>
must be regarded as a distinct and wellcharacterized family paralleling the megalosaurs but not derived from them, and that they cannot be included in that family as has been the general custom.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
